                                                                        <due></due>
                            <votes>0</votes>
                                    <watches>0</watches>
                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13178428" author="thecarlhall" created="Mon, 2 Jan 2012 15:46:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;When the validation chain calls down to UpdateWidgetValidator.validateIfWidgetAlreadyExists, the call to widgetService.getWidgetByUrl hits Spring bean proxy code but is unable to call getWidgetByUrl (java.lang.reflect.InvocationTargetException).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13178436" author="raminder" created="Mon, 2 Jan 2012 16:00:46 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks Carl for digging into this. If you have solution to display a error message to the user that this is not allowed or to disable editing of URL in such cases please provide the patch. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13178445" author="thecarlhall" created="Mon, 2 Jan 2012 16:27:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;d love to work up a patch but don&apos;t have one yet. I want to make sure I understand the surround semantics before I submit a patch. Is this method not allowed by some defined method access logic somewhere? Would it be preferred to disabled editing of the URL, display an error message on edit or both?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13178453" author="raminder" created="Mon, 2 Jan 2012 16:49:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The UpdateWidgetValidator check is not working property for new URLs also. There will be some bug there. As of my understanding, Admis should be allowed to update the URL of existing gadgets as existing gadget link may be boken and if the new URL is not working request need to be redirected to error page. As a improvement, We need to update the metadata also according to new gadget. Look into add widget page for that. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13178491" author="thecarlhall" created="Mon, 2 Jan 2012 18:07:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The &apos;afterInvocation&apos; permission check performed by Spring after the widget is retrieved from widgetService.getWidgetByUrl(widget.getUrl()) fails. I&apos;ve tracked this down to RavePermissionEvaluator.hasPermission. Checking the permission of the returned widget returns false because the widget found is null (null is expected for new URLs). Should RavePermissionEvaluator.hasPermission return false for all checked permissions on null objects?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13178761" author="raminder" created="Tue, 3 Jan 2012 14:48:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Widget found check is to see if the widget is already registered and if i use existing widget its giving me right error. I dont think hasPermission should return false for new URL. I will look into to code to get better understanding. Similar validation checks would be in register new widget and it works there.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13185355" author="raminder" created="Fri, 13 Jan 2012 00:22:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Finally found the problem and it was with  @PostAuthorize(&quot;hasPermission(returnObject, &apos;read&apos;)&quot;)  in WidgetService. If the Widget object is null hasPemission throws 403 Access is denied as described here &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.springsource.org/browse/SEC-1525&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://jira.springsource.org/browse/SEC-1525&lt;/a&gt;. To fix this i need to change it to @PostAuthorize(&quot;returnObject == null or hasPermission(returnObject, &apos;read&apos;)&quot;) .&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13185365" author="raminder" created="Fri, 13 Jan 2012 01:10:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Updated WidgetService&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13214691" author="mfranklin" created="Thu, 23 Feb 2012 14:40:58 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Closing old resolved issues&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
